	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Arion</h1>
	<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		<div id="contentSub2"></div>
		
		<div id="jump-to-nav"></div>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">Jump to search</a>
		<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article is about the Greek poet. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Arion_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Arion (disambiguation)">Arion (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/Orion_(mythology)" title="Orion (mythology)">Orion</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_(1825-1905)_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_(1855).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg/220px-William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="141" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg/330px-William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg/440px-William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="920" data-file-height="590" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_(1825-1905)_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_(1855).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i>Arion on a sea horse</i>, by <a href="/wiki/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau" title="William-Adolphe Bouguereau">William-Adolphe Bouguereau</a> (1855)</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg/220px-Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="135" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg/330px-Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5e/Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg 2x" data-file-width="372" data-file-height="229" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i>Arion riding a Dolphin</i>, by <a href="/wiki/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer" title="Albrecht Dürer">Albrecht Dürer</a> circa. 1514</div></div></div>
<p><b>Arion</b> (<span class="rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title="Help:IPA/English">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="/ə/: &#39;a&#39; in &#39;about&#39;">ə</span><span title="/ˈ/: primary stress follows">ˈ</span><span title="&#39;r&#39; in &#39;rye&#39;">r</span><span title="/aɪ/: &#39;i&#39; in &#39;tide&#39;">aɪ</span><span title="/ə/: &#39;a&#39; in &#39;about&#39;">ə</span><span title="&#39;n&#39; in &#39;nigh&#39;">n</span></span>/</a></span></span>; <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>: <span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek language text"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BC%88%CF%81%CE%AF%CF%89%CE%BD" class="extiw" title="wikt:Ἀρίων">Ἀρίων</a></span>) was a <a href="/wiki/Kitharode" class="mw-redirect" title="Kitharode">kitharode</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">ancient Greece</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysiac</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a> credited with inventing the <a href="/wiki/Dithyramb" title="Dithyramb">dithyramb</a>: "As a literary composition for chorus dithyramb was the creation of Arion of Corinth,"<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The islanders of <a href="/wiki/Lesbos_Island" class="mw-redirect" title="Lesbos Island">Lesbos</a> claimed him as their native son, but Arion found a patron in <a href="/wiki/Periander" title="Periander">Periander</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tyrant" title="Tyrant">tyrant</a> of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Corinth" title="Ancient Corinth">Corinth</a>. Although notable for his musical inventions, Arion is chiefly remembered for the fantastic <a href="/wiki/Myth" title="Myth">myth</a> of his kidnapping by pirates and miraculous rescue by <a href="/wiki/Dolphin" title="Dolphin">dolphins</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Folklore" title="Folklore">folktale</a> motif.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Herodotus (1.23) says "Arion was second to none of the lyre-players in his time and was also the first man we know of to compose and name the <a href="/wiki/Dithyramb" title="Dithyramb">dithyramb</a> and teach it in Corinth". However J.H. Sleeman observes of the dithyramb, or circular chorus, "It is first mentioned by <a href="/wiki/Archilochus" title="Archilochus">Archilochus</a> (c 665 BC) … Arion flourished at least 50 years later … probably gave it a more artistic form, adding a chorus of 50 people, personating satyrs… who danced around an altar of Dionysus. He was doubtless the first to introduce the dithyramb into Corinth".<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Armand_D%27Angour" title="Armand D&#39;Angour">Armand D'Angour</a> notes that Arion's contribution to the reform of the dithyramb, which was eventually performed in a circle and called <i>kuklios choros</i>, was recognised by ancient sources by the fact that they named his father 'Kukleus' ('Circle-man').<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Arion is also associated with the origins of tragedy: of <a href="/wiki/Solon" title="Solon">Solon</a> John the Deacon reports: “Arion of Methymna first introduced the drama [i.e. action] of tragedy, as Solon indicated in his poem entitled <i>Elegies</i>".<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2 id="mw-toc-heading">Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>
